Hi,

1. and 3. Any references to NSGA-II are leftovers from someone&#39;s code 
that were merged and not cleaned yet. Please ignore them and let me know 
where they are, so I can remove them from the repo.

2. Yes.

4. The first two ways are basically correct. Recurrent networks have 
infinite depth and should be activated in continuous manner. They are 
not supposed to stabilize. You can always have a hardcoded limit, like 
16 and activate this many times. It should work for any topology.

5. Use Genome::Save(). The method is also present in the Python object, 
so if &quot;g&quot; is a Genome, then use g.Save(&quot;filename&quot;). To load a genome, 
put the filename in the constructor arguments.

6. Use viz.Draw(). It will return a NumPy array with the NN drawn on it. 
There is no drawing code callable from C++ yet.

Peter



